item.title: 4S Battery Pack
item.description:
EDIT: This is a work in progress. Things will be added or changed.

This 4S battery pack meant to supply around 12 volts or emulate a vehicle battery. 4 battery packs wired in parallel should be able to start a car. I use it to charge my phone, charge a dead car battery enough to start it or anything that can use 10 - 14vdc. Everything is designed to be fairly easy to print. It uses a JST-XH balance connector for balance charging the pack on a RC hobby charger. I used the LFP26650EV LiFePO4 batteries from K2 energy.

Print Settings:
Battery Tray
Material - ASA
Layer height - 0.2mm
Line Width - 0.4mm
Nozzle Temp - 240C
Bed - 110C
Print Speed - 25mm\s
Bed Adhesion - ASA Juice (10g ASA p/ 100ml Acetone)

Battery Pack Body
Material - ASA
Layer height - 0.2mm
Line Width - 0.4mm
Nozzle Temp - 240C
Bed - 110C
Print Speed - 30mm\s
Bed Adhesion - ASA Juice (10g ASA p/ 100ml Acetone)

Battery Pack Cap
Material - ASA
Layer height - 0.2mm
Line Width - 0.4mm
Nozzle Temp - 240C
Bed - 110C
Print Speed - 20mm\s
Bed Adhesion - ASA Juice (10g ASA p/ 100ml Acetone)

Construction Notes:
1st. - Print all the necessary pieces. 2 battery trays, a battery pack body and a battery pack cap.

2nd. - Assemble the battery trays.
 a. - Solder together the contacts as shown in the pictures. I add wires for the balance connectors now because it's easier than doing it when everything is assembled.
 b. - Glue together the two battery trays back-to-back. One side should be flat and one side should have two holes through it. Make sure not to get glue in the slots for the battery contacts or they may not slide in on the next step. Refer to the pictures if necessary.
 c. - Slide in and glue the battery contacts in place. Refer to the pictures if necessary.

3rd. - Put the battery tray in the body and solder all the wires in. I used this wire as the main hookup wire to the battery and a dean's connector. You can use any connector you would like. I included this page as a reference to how balance connectors are wired. Additionally, the pictures can be used as a reference.

4th. - Screw the cap on. The holes should fit #4 or M2.6 fasteners. The screws in the picture I ordered from McMaster.

item.title: SteelSeries Arctis Pro Wireless Gaming Headset Speaker Plate Personalization Reference
item.description:
I recreated the headphone cup caps (they may be called “Speaker Plates” for my SteelSeries Arctis Pro Wireless. It maybe be possible to FDM print these with a 0.4 mm nozzle, but I have not attempted it yet. I just wanted to try and recreate something very close to the originals so that I could use them as reference going forward.

It is advisable to print these with something smaller than a 0.4 mm nozzle if you have it available, or attempt it with a resin printer. Better yet remix it using some of the dimensions that you can pull from the mesh and create a version that is optimized for FDM or whatever other form or 3D printing you prefer.

I have not found any magnets that could be used in conjunction with this model to fully recreate the speaker plates, but I will update the listing when/if I do.

item.title: Spool holder for Ender3 v2 and other
item.description:
Hello everyone. My English is not very good. So I apologize if I misspell. I am using Ender3 v2. The filament spool holder of this one is a little small. Sometimes noises occur when I insert a spool of filament. I feel the need to constantly check the printer to the left of these sounds. That's why I made this reel holder. There are 2 versions here. One with adapter, the other without adapter. Personally, I use the one without adapter and I am satisfied. The nut is compatible with both versions. I haven't tested the one with the adapter. Here I am sharing the Fusion 360 files. Please check again before printing.

V1 (without adapter) are 3 parts,
V2 (with adapter) are 4 parts.

The nut is compatible with both.

I preferred to use PETG instead of PLA.

Herkese merhaba. Arkadaşlar ben Ender3 v2 kullanıyorum. Bunun filament makara tutacağı biraz küçük. Filament makarası taktığım zaman bazen sesler oluyor. Bu seslerden dolayı sürekli yazıcıyı kontrol etme gereği duyuyorum.Bu yüzden bu makara tutacağını yaptım. Burada 2 versiyon bulunuyor. Bir tanesi adaptörlü, diğeri adaptörsüz. Şahsen ben adaptörsüz olanı kullanıyorum ve memnunum. Somun her iki versiyona uyumlu. Adaptörlü olanını test etmedim. Burada Fusion 360 dosyalarını paylaşıyorum. Lütfen baskı yapmadan önce tekrar kontrol edin.

V1 olan parçalar adaptörsüz 3 parça, V2 olan parçalar adaptörlü 4 parça. Somun her ikisinede uyumlu.

Ben PLA yerine PETG kullanmayı tercih ettim.

item.title: Ethernet Breakout Enclosures (PCB)
item.description:
These little enclosures are for the PCB-style ethernet breakout boards that are design for pin-headers. When you need a bunch of small wires I'm a big fan of ethernet cable as it's generally fairly durable, reasonable insulated, and very cheap and easy to get. I use these on my 3D printers and I would strongly encourage stranded ethernet cable for things that are moving a lot.

These are a bit of labor. You'll probably buy the PCBs (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B079L6C96M) and jacks (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07CWJZSPC) separately. You'll need to solder them together as well as solder on pin headers or wires however I'm in for less then $1 a piece.

The case is design so you can plug ping in directly from the top as you would expect or loop them through the back of the case. This helps alleviate some of the pressure on the pins.

item.title: Clean Dirty Dishwasher Sign
item.description:
There's a lot of designs for dishwasher clean/dirty signs, but I need a physical reminder when not to accidentally put dirty dishes in with the clean ones.

This flips down in the way of the handle so I notice when opening the dishwasher.

There's two 11x2 mm holes for inserting magnets into the print; I paused at layer 17 with a 0.2mm layer height.

I used my cricut to cut out labels for the sign; the files should be resized to 2.385 x 1 inch to fit on the hinge.

item.title: Hanging tray for Passap E6000
item.description:
The Passap E6000 has a small, narrow tray screwed to its right support post, for the pushers and miscellaneous small tools; it's cluttered. I wanted my tools to be more accessible, so I created a tray that hangs very securely on the leading edge of the existing one. The tools are now much more visible, and readily accessible. Best of all, no screws or glue are necessary to keep the tray in its place, and you can remove it any time you please.

Print in PLA at standard settings. I used 15% infill, 10% is probably just as good.
